<H5>  CNG Vehicle Estimate Findings </H5>
  In estimating the CNG vehicle introduction and operating 
costs in accordance with the premises cited earlier, as is shown 
in the summary chart that follows, we found that compared with 
existing vehicles, the average annual cost and the total costs 
for trucks and buses are fairly high. 
  First of all, if we look at the figures for trucks, in 
contrast to an average annual cost of &yen;880,000 for existing 
trucks, for a simple purchase case, without policy-type 
assistance measures, the cost at an annual production level of 
100 units is &yen;1.73 million, a little less than twice that of 
current vehicle cost. If annual production is expanded to 1,000 
units, the average annual introduction and operating cost falls 
to &yen;1.31 million, around 1.5 times that of existing 
vehicles. If annual production is expanded to 10,000 units, the 
average annual cost for introduction and operation falls to 
&yen;1.12 million, around 1.3 times that of existing vehicles. 
However, as it stands, it is hard to believe that CNG vehicles 
are going to be popularized with road transport carriers. 
  Accordingly, when automobile and corporate tax reduction 
measures are taken as steps to promote popularization, average 
annual cost falls to &yen;1.08 million on the basis of an annual 
production level of 10,000 units, and if a lease system which 
incorporates fiscal-investment-and-loan financing is added, the 
cost falls to &yen;1.02 million. Furthermore, if a 
fixed-rate-interest subsidy (3%) is added, the average 
annual 
cost is lowered to &yen;960,000, 1.09 times that of existing 
vehicles. Thus, with complete commitment of the main assistance 
measures assumed initially, it is possible to shrink the 
disparity in cost with existing vehicles to around &yen;80,000 
per year. 
  In looking at CNG buses the same holds true, the required 
costs also swell in comparison to existing vehicles. Compared 
with trucks, the expendable item cost for existing buses and the 
low-pollution buses are relatively small, and so this will 
shrink the cost disparity with existing vehicles. However, even 
with all policy support measures (fixed-rate-interest subsidy of 
3%), and production expanded to 1,000 units, CNG buses 
will be 
cheaper than existing buses, and it is to be anticipated that 
they will replace existing vehicles within the new vehicle 
replacement frameworks already in place. 



