<ABS>  Japan </ABS>
<DATE1>   17 February 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> Aerospace </F>
<H3> <TI>   IHI Delivers New Jet Engine ``F100-220E'' for ASDF's Intercept Fighter F-15 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94FE0104B Tokyo NIKKAN KOGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 Sep 93 p 
19 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94FE0104B </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKAN KOGYO SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy Industries Co., Ltd. (IHI) 
completed the F100-220E, an improved version of the F100-100 jet 
engine for the Air Self-Defense Force's (ASDF) intercept fighter 
F-15, and delivered the first engine to the Defense Agency on 29 
October. The new engine is equipped with a digital electronics 
control device (DEEC), which digitally controls all functions of 
the engine. The new engine's main feature is that its 
reliability and controllability have been substantially improved 
over the F100 engine, which was developed in 1975. 
  The DEEC directly controls the engine pressure ratio (EPR), 
using a computer to maintain the air-fuel ratio at the optimum 
level under all flight conditions. As a result, full engine 
performance is guaranteed at every instance to enable the pilot 
to control the throttle with complete freedom. Moreover, the 
DEEC contributes to the improvement of serviceability and 
durability, as well as life-cycle cost. 
  IHI will deliver a total of nine engines this fiscal year to 
the Defense Agency, including the first one it just delivered, 
and 17 additional engines during the next fiscal year. 

</TEXT>

